percent failed to name any members of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>, 20 percent could name four and more than one in 10 erroneously made the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> a member _ Only 55 percent identified <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as the nation where apartheid is an official policy Americans generally did better on environmental questions, with nearly 95 percent knowing that damage to the ozone layer would have worldwide effect; 73 percent knowing wind patterns were responsible for spreading the nuclear fallout from <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>; and 68 percent identifying acid rain as a particular problem in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. While nearly 70 per cent of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> tested agreed that the ability to read a map was a necessity in today's world, more than one third could not pick out the westernmost city on a simple map, the survey indicated.
