erent,'' she said of comparisons between West European nations and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` It is not possible to have a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. What is possible is for the 12 countries of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> steadily to work more closely together on things we do better together, so that we can trade better together.'' She said <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s chief official, erred in predicting that within a decade 80 percent of national decisions by member nations would be taken on a Europe-wide basis. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said no need existed for uniformity of sales taxes. As for an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> central bank, she said, that would mean surrendering `` fundamental economic decisions to another country... That I will not do. Opinion polls show British voters are less enthusiastic about closer ties within the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> than, say, the West Germans or the French.
